<figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F357ae3cd-101c-4e00-b9d2-fcfcaddd68bf_1000x628.png" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux. 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/Dc4G_ae-0Qjlmjy-ieOJDdm5LNWmIegdc8AQ04T_R_8=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd184NDgsY19saW1pdCxmX3dlYnAscV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkYzNTdhZTNjZC0xMDFjLTRlMDAtYjlkMi1mY2ZjYWRkZDY4YmZfMTAwMHg2MjgucG5n 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/OvtdchsnpqHHBVULWdQ6xXf7uE2IOwWi-KLRnKXth94=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xMjcyLGNfbGltaXQsZl93ZWJwLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGMzU3YWUzY2QtMTAxYy00ZTAwLWI5ZDItZmNmY2FkZGQ2OGJmXzEwMDB4NjI4LnBuZw== 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/XxLuRFs5z2sPXTDcUMM6ogIILYLLT6JjEW2Lz_B01CA=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl93ZWJwLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGMzU3YWUzY2QtMTAxYy00ZTAwLWI5ZDItZmNmY2FkZGQ2OGJmXzEwMDB4NjI4LnBuZw== 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/lr2UiWouonSjO0vYVYwObPu7ba1E-" width="505" alt="" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/GKV82fl9RA2a-qCYJ8QTy3SD7-6-SBGrh5cVlmztd9Y=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd180MjQsY19saW1pdCxmX2F1dG8scV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkYzNTdhZTNjZC0xMDFjLTRlMDAtYjlkMi1mY2ZjYWRkZDY4YmZfMTAwMHg2MjgucG5n 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/WAP4Ng7UQkHXqKaMZH_6DcvHhu0tZHg3N_OA0OlRLC8=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd184NDgsY19saW1pdCxmX2F1dG8scV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkYzNTdhZTNjZC0xMDFjLTRlMDAtYjlkMi1mY2ZjYWRkZDY4YmZfMTAwMHg2MjgucG5n 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/rzpS3avBJS_9ua3IdIwP-2x2_ 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/lr2UiWouonSjO0vYVYwObPu7ba1E- 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a></figure><p>Recently on Twitter—er I suppose I mean “X”—writers were revisiting the old debate about dialogue tags. On the one side, people argue reading constant “[he/she/they] said”s is boring. Shouldn’t writers vary their language and say things in fresh ways? On the other, there’s the argument that the simple and noble “x said” tag is there to get out of the way. Good dialogue conveys meaning by itself without needing verbs or adjectives. The tag is there merely to signal who is speaking, not to show off.</p><p>For the most part, I side with <a href="https://twitter.com/TheLincoln/status/1679331431917420544" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">the latter group.</a> Having your characters constantly mumble, grumble, shout, snipe, asseverate, and ejaculate is at best best distracting and often unintentionally hilarious. </p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F9fb825f2-5c47-4e80-b07e-fafdb3b9f034_1102x625.jpeg" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/IXDDopbdSkNzx3fa_ 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/F3x2sJydnLwafhcSlsXvLfvHCqsTHNoN4oZqsAMi-kU=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd184NDgsY19saW1pdCxmX3dlYnAscV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkY5ZmI4MjVmMi01YzQ3LTRlODAtYjA3ZS1mYWZkYjNiOWYwMzRfMTEwMng2MjUuanBlZw== 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/B79HmKqBoYd6- 1272w, https://reader.miniflux. 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux." width="407" alt="" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/lS7q6hSJ_sLb-A9wAHvDIlmq7aAAtnoKS3WlxBYO2_Y=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd180MjQsY19saW1pdCxmX2F1dG8scV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkY5ZmI4MjVmMi01YzQ3LTRlODAtYjA3ZS1mYWZkYjNiOWYwMzRfMTEwMng2MjUuanBlZw== 424w, https://reader.miniflux. 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/REis94lbbbY7BVv6_ 1272w, https://reader.miniflux. 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a><figcaption>Excerpt of an infamous Harry Potter fan fiction…</figcaption></figure><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff2dda16f-5245-49de-b7aa-4778963e46e8_640x426.jpeg" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux. 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/aGzrORY83DjlrNtQgsLhbNamFTXpdlX9ag2ene_Lkws=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd184NDgsY19saW1pdCxmX3dlYnAscV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkZmMmRkYTE2Zi01MjQ1LTQ5ZGUtYjdhYS00Nzc4OTYzZTQ2ZThfNjQweDQyNi5qcGVn 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/Wm4Fjzd984JkVQ_sPz2B0GrLErcpBQyTuh_btVqJwpw=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xMjcyLGNfbGltaXQsZl93ZWJwLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGZjJkZGExNmYtNTI0NS00OWRlLWI3YWEtNDc3ODk2M2U0NmU4XzY0MHg0MjYuanBlZw== 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/Tm8e8czv7y8pXHkhhu8C384VgE2KE-yfahi5zeEoWGk=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl93ZWJwLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGZjJkZGExNmYtNTI0NS00OWRlLWI3YWEtNDc3ODk2M2U0NmU4XzY0MHg0MjYuanBlZw== 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux." width="404" alt="" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/r- 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/xSFyxB99GEwgE96dIPilukjZzhOyW_YmW4DNnW06gdU=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd184NDgsY19saW1pdCxmX2F1dG8scV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkZmMmRkYTE2Zi01MjQ1LTQ5ZGUtYjdhYS00Nzc4OTYzZTQ2ZThfNjQweDQyNi5qcGVn 848w, https://reader.miniflux. 1272w, https://reader.miniflux. 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a><figcaption>…although maybe we can blame the source material. </figcaption></figure><p>Often “said” thesaurusing leads to impossible actions like characters “gasping” or “wheezing” or “sighing” whole paragraphs of dialogue. (Try that at home, folks.) Other times it is just redundant. <em>“I agree,” she agreed.</em> Yes, I got that. </p><p>It’s useful to remember that we don’t read every word equally. Our brains gloss over some language, just registering the important information rather than lingering on each word. With “said” tags your brain registers who speaks and moves on. “Asked” and “replied” are also fairly neutral. But if characters are <em>shouting</em> or <em>grumbling</em> or <em>screeching</em>, then the brain slows down. </p><p>So, yes, I agree that said is typically best. However, since this newsletter is called <em>Counter Craft</em>, I do want to give some contrary advice and agree somewhat with the “too many saids is boring” crowd. Because it’s true that reading tons of said tags can be both dull and unnecessary. In large part that’s because some writers tag too much. </p><p>Emerging writers sometimes feel the need to tag every line of dialogue even if the reader has other indicators of who is speaking. There’s no need to do this, unless it’s for rhythm or pacing. If the reader knows who is speaking based on the dialogue or actions, then you can normally skip the tag. I’m currently reading <em>Dr. No</em> by the great Percival Everett and here’s a section from the start of the book where the narrator, a math professor who studies nothing, meets a billionaire who wants to be a Bond villain: </p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fcfc9b539-c9d1-4443-8e21-443a30df313d_796x456.jpeg" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/9IPL_4mVf6QwvXuacHA7_ 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/4jo1vK_ 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/V_p9vF7sQy-1DRsyYnMjdMi-Xks0q-TIyyub44ANW7k=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xMjcyLGNfbGltaXQsZl93ZWJwLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGY2ZjOWI1MzktYzlkMS00NDQzLThlMjEtNDQzYTMwZGYzMTNkXzc5Nng0NTYuanBlZw== 1272w, https://reader.miniflux. 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/o8cLwJYw52pCYzr1JWDdUGDb-" width="525" alt="" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/L78aOcJL9raoKN6A3gHzXbPFC-mKiYQ-eKwr0mL4orU=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd180MjQsY19saW1pdCxmX2F1dG8scV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkZjZmM5YjUzOS1jOWQxLTQ0NDMtOGUyMS00NDNhMzBkZjMxM2RfNzk2eDQ1Ni5qcGVn 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/_-6xg5SgA8zC0dq2lX16atFPD0uaO_xsQBdIroVUHEk=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd184NDgsY19saW1pdCxmX2F1dG8scV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkZjZmM5YjUzOS1jOWQxLTQ0NDMtOGUyMS00NDNhMzBkZjMxM2RfNzk2eDQ1Ni5qcGVn 848w, https://reader.miniflux. 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/o8cLwJYw52pCYzr1JWDdUGDb- 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a></figure><p>In this passage, there is no “Sill Said” tags. Instead we get Sill’s actions of poking the air with a spoon and looking around to indicate when he’s speaking. (<a href="https://bookshop.org/p/books/dr-no-percival-everett/17889374?ean=9781644452080" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">You can purchase Dr. No here.</a> It’s very fun!)</p><p>You can also notice plenty of the dialogue above is simply untagged. Again, if your reader knows who is speaking why bother with a tag? The other novel I’m currently reading is the lovely and haunting <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/p/books/ripe-sarah-rose-etter/18992345?ean=9781668011638" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Ripe </a></em><a href="https://bookshop.org/p/books/ripe-sarah-rose-etter/18992345?ean=9781668011638" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">by Sarah Rose Etter</a>, which is narrated by a woman who is followed everywhere by a black hole. In this passage, only a single tag is used yet there’s no confusion about who is speaking: </p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbda3c743-3b48-456c-8dbb-2c069fffbf52_816x536.jpeg" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/rqzEz_ 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/X6vrVYrBa4Cl8Nf7rIACBv-kn_gmbQk4Cd4zXSLFNSU=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd184NDgsY19saW1pdCxmX3dlYnAscV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkZiZGEzYzc0My0zYjQ4LTQ1NmMtOGRiYi0yYzA2OWZmZmJmNTJfODE2eDUzNi5qcGVn 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/1Ho9o7E2DIEkciZXPP33ABwvykUWV35s1UmZub6k-mg=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xMjcyLGNfbGltaXQsZl93ZWJwLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGYmRhM2M3NDMtM2I0OC00NTZjLThkYmItMmMwNjlmZmZiZjUyXzgxNng1MzYuanBlZw== 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/WhaJP4MEmpgBL_ 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux." width="453" alt="" srcset="https://reader.miniflux. 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/yrTNovJCssWRVwlSbgTL5bVVe7suS09_VM8LSzZCwAM=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd184NDgsY19saW1pdCxmX2F1dG8scV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkZiZGEzYzc0My0zYjQ4LTQ1NmMtOGRiYi0yYzA2OWZmZmJmNTJfODE2eDUzNi5qcGVn 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/2MGvrxzH0_bCpbTcde- 1272w, https://reader.miniflux. 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a></figure><p>The one tag Etter uses is not said, yet is an example of when it is actually good to vary tags. First, sparingly! Second, when another verb adds meaning. <em>“It’s going okay,” I said </em>would convey something quite different than <em>“It’s going okay,” I choke out</em>, right? (<a href="https://bookshop.org/p/books/ripe-sarah-rose-etter/18992345?ean=9781668011638" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Check out Ripe here!</a>) </p><p>Here’s two more examples of useful non-said tags that I always think of when this debate comes up. The first is from Hemingway in <em>The Sun Also Rises</em>: </p><blockquote><p><em>&#34;This is a good place,&#34; he said.</em></p><p><em>&#34;There&#39;s a lot of liquor,&#34; I agreed.</em></p></blockquote><p>The second from <em>Jesus’ Son</em> by Denis Johnson, when the narrator goes to “[talk] to a man about vasectomies”: </p><blockquote><p><em>“You have to be sure,” he said.</em></p><p><em>“I’m never getting anybody pregnant again. I know that much.”</em></p><p><em>“Would you like to make an appointment?”</em></p><p><em>“Would you like to give me the money?”</em></p><p><em>“It won’t take long to save the money.”</em></p><p><em>“It would take me forever to save the money,” I corrected him.</em></p></blockquote><p>Both of these tags are good jokes and also character indicating. (This isn’t false modesty on Johnson’s narrator, a heroin addict known as Fuckhead. It really would take him forever to save up the money.) But the jokes only work because of the surprise of the verb. If all of your other dialogue is either untagged or “saids,” then a new verb will have useful impact in the text. If you are constantly varying verbs—if your text reads <em>he mumbled, she rebutted, he retorted, she agreed, he gasped </em>then the individual tags probably won’t reveal much except the reader’s annoyance.</p><p>At least that’s what I say. </p><p>Counter Craft is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.</p><p><em>If you like this newsletter, <a href="https://countercraft.substack.com/subscribe" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">consider subscribing</a> or checking out my recent science fiction novel </em><a href="https://bookshop.org/books/the-body-scout/9780316628723" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">The Body Scout</a><em> that </em>The New York Times<em> called “Timeless and original…a wild ride, sad and funny, surreal and intelligent.”</em></p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/